# Git Workflow

## Branching

- **One branch per feature / step.** Before starting work, create a branch off
  up-to-date `main`. Naming: `feat/<slug>`, `fix/<slug>`, `chore/<slug>`.
  Plan steps: `feat/stepN-<slug>` (e.g. `feat/step8-audit-trail`).
- A branch may contain **many focused commits** (model → API → tests → docs).
  Do not squash unrelated features into one commit; do not mix features on one branch.

## Commits

- Commit as you go after each meaningful chunk passes its check.
- Use conventional messages: `feat(backend): …`, `fix(web): …`, `chore: …`,
  with a short body when useful.
- Never commit secrets (`.env`, credentials).

## Push (required)

- **After development on a branch, always push** (`git push -u origin HEAD` on
  first push, then `git push`). Do not leave finished work only local.
- Push after completing a step/feature, and at other necessary times (device
  switch, end of session, before asking the user to review).

## Merge

- When the branch is **complete** (acceptance checks pass) **or** at another
  necessary time, open a PR into `main` and **merge** it (`gh pr create` then
  `gh pr merge`), unless the user says they will merge themselves.
- Prefer merge commits or squash as the repo already uses; default to
  `gh pr merge --merge` unless the user prefers squash.
- After merge: switch to `main`, `git pull`, delete the local feature branch if done,
  then start the next feature on a **new** branch from updated `main`.

## Trunk

- Trunk is `main` → `origin/main`. Never force-push `main`.
- Never use `git push --force` on shared branches unless the user explicitly asks.
